  "local_port": 52950,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why do converts to Islam say that they have reverted to Islam?",
  "response": "In Islam, when individuals embrace the faith, they often describe their transition as \"reverting\" to Islam rather than \"converting\" to it. This distinction is rooted in Islamic theology and worldview, and understanding it requires exploring several key concepts:\n\n### 1. The Concept of **Fitrah**\nIslam teaches that every human being is born with an innate disposition towards monotheism and recognition of one God, known as **fitrah**. This inherent nature predisposes individuals to seek and acknowledge the truth of God's existence and to live in accordance with divine guidance.\n\n- **Quranic Reference:**  \n  Allah says in the Quran:  \n  *\"So direct your face toward the religion, inclining to truth. [Adhere to] the fitrah of Allah upon which He has created [all] people. No change should there be in the creation of Allah.\"*  \n  (Quran 30:30)\n\nThis verse emphasizes that the natural state (**fitrah**) is one of submission to God, and no inherent change is intended in this divine creation.\n\n### 2. **Original Submission to God**\nMuslims believe that the first human beings, Adam and Eve, submitted to God's will, establishing the original relationship between humanity and the Creator. This submission is seen as the baseline state for all humans.\n\n- **Prophetic Tradition:**  \n  A well-known hadith (saying of the Prophet Muhammad) states:  \n  *\"Every child is born upon fitrah (natural disposition), but his parents make him a Jew, Christian or Magian.\"*  \n  (Sahih Muslim)\n\nThis underscores the belief that outside of cultural or societal influences, every person is innately aligned with the monotheistic truth.\n\n### 3. **Reverting to the Natural State**\nGiven the belief in **fitrah**, when a person embraces Islam, they are viewed as returning to their original, natural state of belief in one God. Hence, the term \"revert\" (often translated from the Arabic word \"**Irtidad**\" or \"**I'tilam**\") is used to signify this return rather than a conversion from one distinct religion to another.\n\n- **Theological Implication:**  \n  Conversion implies moving from one separate religion to another. However, since Muslims consider the truth of Islam to be consistent with the original monotheistic belief endowed by **fitrah**, embracing Islam is seen as restoring one's original faith rather than adopting a new one.\n\n### 4. **Unity of Abrahamic Faiths**\nIslam recognizes and respects previous Abrahamic religions\u2014Judaism and Christianity\u2014as having originated from the same divine source. Prophets like Abraham, Moses, and Jesus are acknowledged in Islamic tradition.\n\n- **Quranic Perspective:**  \n  The Quran speaks of the \"People of the Book\" (Ahl al-Kitab) and acknowledges that Islam completes and perfects the earlier revelations.\n\nThis perspective fosters the view that embracing Islam is a return to the foundational monotheistic belief shared across these faiths.\n\n### 5. **Terminology Preference**\nThe preference for \"revert\" over \"convert\" also serves to emphasize continuity rather than change. It highlights the belief that everyone is inherently predisposed to Islam and that embracing it is aligning with one's true nature.\n\n### Summary\nIn essence, when Muslims refer to embracing Islam as \"reverting,\" they are expressing the belief that they are returning to their original, inherent state of submission to one God as intended in their **fitrah**. This theological stance frames Islam as the natural and primal faith of humanity, rather than a new religion adopted from an external origin.",
